in Cilicia] There is no other account of this attempt on the Cydnus. Caesar marched from Egypt into Syria (De Bello Alexandrino, c. 33), and from Syria he went to Tarsus in Cilicia, which is on the river Cydnus (Id. 66, where there is some contradiction). His road from the Cydnus to the table land of Asia was through the gorge in the Taurus on the upper course of the Cydnus. The story in Appian is that when Caesar, after the battle of Pharsalus, was crossing the Hellespont in small boats. 118 was met by C. Cassius with seventy triremes, who instead of attacking Caesar gave up his fleet and begged for mex-cy (Appian, B. C. ii. c. 88). Comp. Sueten. Caesar, c. 63; Dion, 42, c. 6.
